explanation:
Average power is equivalent to RMS power
<br/><br/>$$
\begin{aligned}
&I_{r m s}=\frac{I}{\sqrt{2}}=\frac{5}{\sqrt{2}} \\\\
&P=I_{r m s}^2 R=\frac{25}{2} \times 4=50 \mathrm{~W}
\end{aligned}
$$

Current flowing through inductor,
<br/><br/>$$
I(t)=e^{a t}+e^{b t}
$$
<br/><br/>Voltage across inductor,
<br/><br/>$$
\begin{aligned}
&V(t)=L \frac{d I(t)}{d t}=1 \frac{d}{d t}\left[e^{a t}+e^{b t}\right] \\\\
&V(t)=a e^{a t}+b e^{b t}
\end{aligned}
$$

Let voltage across terminal $a b$ is $V$. <br/><br/>Applying KCL at node $a$,
<br/><br/>$$
\begin{aligned}
 \Rightarrow &\frac{V-1}{2}+\frac{V}{2}=3 \\\\
\Rightarrow &V-\frac{1}{2}=3 \\\\
\Rightarrow &V=3.5 \mathrm{~V}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since diode is Forward Bias, so it will be replaced by short circuit wire, and now applying KCL for voltage V.<br/><br/> $\frac{V-4}{2}+\frac{V}{2}+\frac{V+2}{2}=0$
<br/><br/>$$
\begin{aligned}
 \Rightarrow &V=\frac{2}{3} \\\\
&V_0=-V=\frac{-2}{3}
\end{aligned}
$$
